{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_fink_ver02/data/sn82016181/00529045621/1923102702/1015.xml":{"full_text":"WEATHER\nFAIR TONIGHT\nCLOUDY SUNDAY\news\nHOME\nEDITION\ni\ni\nVOL. 2\u2014NO. 305\nWASHINGTON, D. C., SATURDAY, OCTOBER 27, 1923\nONE CENT\nROOSEVELT EXPLAINS \u201cNAVY DAY,f\nTHEODORE ROOSEVELT\nNO RESUMPTION\nOF COMPETITIVE\nBUILDING SEEN\n\"Navy Day, Oct. 27.\"\nPlacards with this cryptic message\nare plastered all over our towns and\ncities\u2014east, west, north and south.\nWhat does\" it mean\nWasn't our\nwhole navy pregram and policy set\ntled two years ago by the Washing\nton conference?\nSeeking the answer to these ques\ntions at the source, I went to see\nTheodore Roosevelt, acting secretary\nof navy during the absence, with an\ninjured foot, of Secretary Denby.\nNavy dav, by the way, also is the\nbirthday anniversary of Roosevelt's\nfamous father, the great \u201cTeddy.\"\n\u201cNavy Day;\" he said, \u201cis a day set\naside especially for infarming the\npublic on the importance and needs\nof the navy. It is a day to catch the\ninterest of citizens everywhere\u2014in\nthe middle west and west as well as\nalong the coast\u2014on our naval devel\nopment.\n\u201cPrior to the conference on naval\nlimitation, our naval programs were\nalways shaped by the tug-of-war be\ntween the big and the little navy\nfolks; between those who wanted us\nto have incomparably the strongest\nnavy on earth ami those who wanted\nvirtually no navy at all.\n\u201cThe arms conference, for the first\ntime, gave us a definite mark at\nIt committed us to a\nwhich to aim.\ndefinite naval policy\u2014that of a navy\nequal to Great Britain\u2019s and 40 per\ncent larger than any other navy.\nNavy Unbalanced\n\u201cAt this time we have not got a\ntreaty navy. Our naval strength is\nnot balanced. We lack essential ele\nments, including mine-laying sub\nmarines,\ncruisers\nscout submarines,\nequipment on\nand certain\nscout\nmodernized\nboard our capital\nships. Our mission is now to create\na balanced and adequate treaty\nnavy.\nWe will undertake no build\ning plans in the unrestricted classes\nwhich might be said to reopen naval\ncompetition, but we must endeavor\nto put ourselves on a party with the\nratio allowed us.1\n\u201cOur navy is the shield which pre\nvents an enemy from striking at our\nvitals.\nIt is also the right arm of\nthe State department.\nBut as an air to civilian progress\nthe navy also is a tremendous factor.\nAndrew Carnegie once said that the\nnavy was responsible for the devel\nopment of the vast steel industry in\nthis country.\n\"The navy was the parent of the\nterrific radio development of the past\nfew years.\nNasy By-Products\n\u201cThe same in aircraft. Army and\nnavy experimentation and develop\nments promise to be invaluable to\nthe development of aircraft\ncivilian uses.\n\u201cThe lesson of Navy dav?\nthis:\nfor\nit is\n\u201cOur freedom, the safety of our\nfamilies, the institutions we prize, all\ndemand a proper defense.\n\"It is my hope that Navy day will\nhelp spread the understanding of\nthat need.\u201d\nDENBY OPPOSES\nSOLDIER BONUS\n\u201cWe hope that our country is not\nto forget those who have suffered\nphysically in the service of the flag.\nI hope the country' will give the best\nof hospital treatment and vocational\ntraining to those who need it, but I\ndo hope that no mercenary spirit will\nprompt any, who are fit and who\nhave not suffered physically, to ask\nfor any form of bonus from the gov\nernment.\"\nDenby today at the\nThus spoke Secretary\nPC\nN\navy Day cere\nmonies before the John Paul Jones\nstatue.\nPreceding the speech, sailors and\nmarines from the fifth regiment at\nQuantico paraded from the navy\nyard to the White House Ellipse for\nmaneuvers and a review.\nWALTON TRIAL THURSDAY\nOKLAHOMA CITY\u2014J. C. Walton,\ni suspended governor, will go on trial\nThursday before the senate, sitting\nas an impeachment court.\nChief Justice J. T. Johnson will\npieside.\nIn the interval Walton has the\nright to file an answer to the 22\ncharges voted by the House.\nTHE WEATHER\nITU K913.\nFair totught\nmuch\n(A TOBER s. 19%\nSunday increasing e\u2018\ngentle to moderst\ning vartable\nYesterday\nchunge\ntemperaturri\nr northerly winds boom\np.\n4 p\nU P\nN p\n10 p\nEEEEE\ndidnight\nl\n58 I\nToday\nm\n59 4 a\n36\n(i a.\n5% i Ha\n*2 10\nBBE8\n44\n43\n41\n43\n47\n2\nENGLAND WILL NOT\nRECOGNIZE REBELS\nI\nFRANCE WILLING\nTO LET GERMANY\nDEFER PAYMENTS\nBut Poincare Is Firm Against\nCutting Total Debt\nBy JOHN DEGANDT\nUnited l\u2019ress Staff Correspondent\nPARIS\u2014 If the proposed ex\npert commission concludes Ger\nmany cannot resume repara\ntions payments soon, France\nwill not oppose revision of the\npayment dates, a semiofficial\nstatement Said today.\nThe gulf separating Franco\nBritish viewpoints on repara\ntions is much deeper than is\ngenerally supposed.\nPoincare does not consider his con\niditional acceptance of the Anglo\nAmerican proposals for an expert\ncommission to examine Germany's\nI capacity to pay as in any way con\nstituting a deviation from his origi\nnal viewpoint.\nI\nWill Retain Control\nFrance insists that the reparations\ncommission, which she controls, must\nremain the final authority.\nFrance welcomes American co-op\neration\u2014but has\nno\nintention of\nabandoning its view that no reduc\ntion in the amount of reparations can\nbe considered and that the questions\nof allied debts and reparations are\nclosely related.\nI\u2019res\nzon Hughes\ncomment today on the Cur\ncorrespondence\na n d\nPremier Baldwin\u2019s Plymouth speech\nstressed an apparent Anglo-Amer\nican understanding against France.\nBritain ami Germany, the news\npapers charge, are trying to bring\nAmerica into the squabble on their\nside.\nA conference of the great powers\nwill be convened before Christmas\nfor the purpose of settling the rep\narations problem finally.\nThi. government\u2019s expression of\nsatisfaction at France\u2019s reply to the\nHughes proposal makes such a con\nference certain.\nEurope\u2019s\nNo time will be lost,\ncritical state demands that.\nInvitations Soon\nOne of the allied governments\nprobably soon will issue invitations\nfor the parley to convene in its capi\ntal. From there it will move to Ber\nlin, to be on the ground.\nUnder the French terms of accept\nance.\nthe reparations commission\nwill appoint the experts from the\ninterested countries, subject to the\ndifferent government's approval.\nThis government was informed of\nthe French attitude before the\nHughes note was sent, it is indi\ncated.\nMorgan is Mentioned\nAt least five powers will be rep\nresented in the conference.\nThe\nUnited States, France and Great\nBritain have practically agreed. Italy\nand Belgium are understood to de\nsire the parley greatly.\nSpeculation as to the American\nrepresentatives on for the confer\nence centers around bankers like J.\nP.\nMorgan and- Norman\nDavi.\nunder secretary of state under Wil\nson.\nNUTRITION CLINICS\nNutrition clinics for school chil\nren, under the direction of the pub\nlic schools health department and\nthe Associated Charities, begin next\nFriday afternoon at the Associated\nCharities building, 11th-st nw.\nAn outline of the health instruc\ntion in District schools appears in\nthe November World\u2019s Work.\nB. 0. SHOWS PROFIT\nFrom a $2,665,952 operating defi\ncit in September, 1922, to a $3,977,\n152 net operating income in Septem\nber of this year, is the record of the\nB. O. railroad, announced today.\nThis is a gain of $6,643,16..\nSAVE THE SHIFTERS!\nNEW YORK\u2014Some of the\ntheatrical\nplaying on\nproductions\nBroadway\nnow\nhave\nreached such a low moral ebb\nthat the very scene shifters\nare being corrupted.\nThat was the charge today\nof Charles P. Sumner, anti\nvice society secretary.\nDAVIS ACCUSERS\nLIARS, HE SAYS\nIN TRIAL TODAY\nFowler and Wampler Clash\nFrequently\n\u201cEvery word my accusers ut\nter is a deliberate lie,\u201d cried\nLieut. 0. T. Davis, head of the\nvice squad, in\nhis trial\non\ncharges of irregularities before\nthe sixth precinct police trial\nboard this morning.\nWords flew fast between Sus\npended Dry Agent Patrick M.\nFowler and Atty. T. Morris\nWampler.\nCharge Lake Evidence\nCharges against Davis were taken\nup first.\nThere were two charges\nand\n13\nspecifications.\nThe fi rst\ncharged fabrication of evidence af\nter a liquor raid.\nW. E. Burrell,\nformer prehibition agent, testified\nthat on Dec. 12, 1922, with Agents\nPackard, Eowler and Pvt. Bauer, he\ncaptured an auto on Rhode Island\nav\nne.\nTwo jars of whisky were\nthrown out by the colored occupants\nof the car.\nAn empty bottle was\ntaken but n< liquor was found, Bur\nrell said.\n\u201cLieut. Davis was called and the\nbottle turned over to him.\nLater,\nat the station house, Davis exhibited\na bottle of liquor and charged the\nnegroes with illegal possession and\ntransportation. They pleaded guilty\nand were sentenced,\u201d Burrell said.\nWhy Delay Charge\nFowler, Jr., and Clark\nGeorge\nPackard corroborated his statements.\n\u201cWhy did you not make this\ncharge before?\nWampler asked.\nreason,\u201d Fowler\n\u201cI can give no\nsaid.\n\u201cDid you not turn in a signed\nstatement to the district attorney\nthat you found a half-pint of liquor\nin the car 1\"\n\u201cI did,\u201d Fowler replied.\nPackard took the stand.\nResents \u201cDirt\u201d\n\u201cI made charge- against Davis be\ncause I won't stand for it when any\nman does me dirt,\u201d he said.\nLieut. Davis, testifying in his own\nbehalf, denied the charge, as did\nSergt. McQuade and Pvt. Bauer.\nThe second specification charged\nLieut. Davis suggested a business\nsign lie placed on suspected premises\nto obtain\nwarrant.\nProhibition\na\nAgents Linton Evans and George\nFowler testified,\nthis charge.\nDavis also denied\nThe trial will not be completed to\nday.\nCharges against the other three\nmen will be taken up later. Asst.\nCorp. Counsel William Mahley and\nCapt. W. E. Sanford and C. L. Flem\nmons are hearing the case.\nWASHINGTON ELM FALLS\nCAMBRIDGE, Ma s. The Wash\nCAMBRIDGE, Ma\nington elm is no more.\nLast Summer the venerable tree\ndied of old age.\nBut every effort\nwas made to keep it withered form\nerect.\nYesterday workmen started to re\nmove limbs which had become a men\nThe rotting vestige of the once\nace.\ngreat tree under which Washington\ntook command of the Continental\narmy crashed to the earth.\nA crowd picked the lifeless trunk\nclean of every scrap of limbs as\nsouvenirs.\nI\nBRITAIN SCOLDS\nFRANCE, BELGIUM\nFOR RHINE POLICY\nFrowns on Help Given to Sep\naratist Movement\nI\nBy LLOYD ALLEN\nUmted Pmss Staff Correspondent\nL ONDO N\u2014Great Britain\nwill not recognize the Rhine\nland republic headed by Josef\nMatthes.\nShe will resist with troops\nany attempt to extend the\nmovement into Cologne, center\nof the British occupation area.\nThe British foreign office doubts\nthe justification of France and Bel\ngium in winking at the rebels\u2019 ef\nforts, if not openly helping them.\nEngland cannot stand quietly by\nand allow the disintegration of Ger\nmany, it was made clear.\nBy CARL D. GROAT\nUnited Press Staff Correspondent\nBERLIN Widespread and bloody\nrioting occurred thruout the Ruhr\ntoday as goevrnment officials await\ned additional information on the\npeace move started in London and\nWashington for settlement of the\nreparations' question.\nBarmen dispatches said seven per-\nsons were killed and 40 wounded in\nscattered fighting in the occupied\nzone.\nCommunists Started It 1\nCommunists, engineering demon-\nstrations of unemployed, started tne\nrioting.\nGerman police are regaining con\ntrol, tho clashes continue in many\ndistricts.\naNtionalists captured Herr Leig\nner, commander of the separatist\narmy, in\nauto near Duren, a\nan\nDusseldorf dispatch says.\nA second car carrying members\nof the provisional government es\ncaped.\nStorm Krupp Plant\nThree were killed and 20 wounded\nwhen workers stormed the Krupp\nplant at Eesen protesting dismissals\nand pay cuts.\nDisorders were reported in Upper\nSilesia, where a general mine strike\nThe workers demand a i\nwas callel.\nstable wage, and guarantees of food 4\nand clothing.\nAn official statement issued at I\nHamburg placed the total killed in i\nrecent communist outbreak at 100.\nDRY GOODS MEN GATHER\nNEW ORLEANS\u2014Optimism\nto the business outlook was\nas\nex\npressed by delegates to the South-\nem Wholesale Dry Goods association\ntoday.\nDEAR SANTA\u2014\nHAMMTON, N. J. The first let-\nter of the season to\n\u2018Santa Claus, I\nNorth Pole.\u201d wa- received by the\npostmaster here today. j\nDAVIS 50 TODAY\nEmployes of the Deartment of f\nof Labor today remembered Sec re-\ntary Davis with a huge boquet of J\nIt is his 50th J\ni\nchrysanthemums,\nbirthday.\nRITZ HOTEL HEAD DIES\nLEEDS, Eng. William Harris, 64 I\nhead of the Ritz-Carlton Hotels, is\ndead here.\nWe Have Selected\nToday\u2019s Best Bargains\nIn Used Cars!\n1\nl\u2019wd Car Dealer\nYou fan never go wrong on a Cerd 4\nCar\u2014if sou wall buy* from a Reputable I 3\n!\u2018*d Car 1-m2er His huaszuaras mi nexs-\nnan\u2019y tat upon Good Will and Conf\ndeuce\nHere ia one of the many rood ways\nwlich ar** advertinid in the Used Car 1 i\ncolumns of th** Classified P'agee-Fnd\nFOKD SEDAN\nI\nguarantee\n\u2014new engia 90 diya guarantee cond\npaiuit upho'stery and tirra. Only $375. i\nCash or terme\nROBEY MOTOR CO.","height":"21676","width":"14432"}}
